"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-31-swimmers-slap-a-race-olympics-21334944\", \"entities\": [{\"sentence\": \"Swimming, on paper at least, looks a relatively straightforward sport - but viewers tuning in from the comfort of their own homesoften have plenty of questions.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 160, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"And chief amongst them is why on Earth some swimmers slap themselves before the start of a race.\", \"from\": 162, \"to\": 258, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Such is the force that the swimmers hit themselves with, that red marks are sometimes visible on an athlete's body afterwards.\", \"from\": 260, \"to\": 386, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for updates from the Paris Olympics 2024  So, why exactly do swimmers, such as those competing at theOlympics, turn their force on their own bodies?\", \"from\": 388, \"to\": 567, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Here is everything you need to know.\", \"from\": 569, \"to\": 605, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Some swimmers chose to slap themselves before a race in order to increase blood flow to certain muscles, which in turn helps with performance.\", \"from\": 607, \"to\": 749, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The shoulders, biceps, triceps and pectorals are essential for swimming so athletes will usually start with these areas.\", \"from\": 751, \"to\": 871, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The legs are typically next to receive the treatment, with the thighs and hamstrings next to benefit from the increased blood flow.\", \"from\": 873, \"to\": 1004, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"However, there is a psychological aspect, too.\", \"from\": 1006, \"to\": 1052, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Matt Barbini, USA's director of performance, previously toldTODAYthat it helps to keep athletes calm and composed whilst they are waiting for the race to get underway.\", \"from\": 1054, \"to\": 1221, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1068, \"end\": 1071, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\", \"score\": 0.9999669339966609, \"rank\": 2.2663159298751e-05, \"text\": \"USA\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Barbini said: 'Anything that sort of kills those in-between moments before the race starts, I think helps keep athletes calm and it helps to distract them from the nerves.'\", \"from\": 1223, \"to\": 1395, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The thinking behind this is that, faced with a long wait on the starting blocks before the start of the race, the act of hitting themselves helps to stave away pressure and thoughts of self-doubt.\", \"from\": 1397, \"to\": 1593, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"It's also been said that a swimmer hitting themselves pre-race is an act of intimidation to their competitors, with loud slapping a display of intimidating and threatening behaviour.\", \"from\": 1595, \"to\": 1777, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Not every swimmer slaps their body before a race though - every athlete has their own individual pre-race routine.\", \"from\": 1779, \"to\": 1893, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"But for those athletes who do hit themselves, they are unlikely to change their routine - especially if they keep on winning.\", \"from\": 1895, \"to\": 2020, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"ArrowMORE:How Andy Murray and Dan Evans 'transformed' into Olympic medal contenders  ArrowMORE:How South Korea's Kim Yeji became the ultimate Olympics fashion icon  ArrowMORE:Remarkable moment a bee nearly ruins archers' gold medal hopes at Olympics  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.\", \"from\": 2022, \"to\": 2383, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2036, \"end\": 2047, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andy_Murray\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.6654281274814414e-23, \"text\": \"Andy Murray\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\", \"Q10833314\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andy_Murray\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Andy_Murray\"}, {\"begin\": 2121, \"end\": 2132, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/South_Korea\", \"score\": 0.9974377306109088, \"rank\": 0.002492813702901548, \"text\": \"South Korea\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/South_Korea\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/South_Korea\"}, {\"begin\": 2135, \"end\": 2138, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kim_Kardashian\", \"score\": 0.7290634430916418, \"rank\": 0.21978095046557797, \"text\": \"Kim\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kim_Kardashian\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kim_Kardashian\"}, {\"begin\": 2139, \"end\": 2143, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Itzy\", \"score\": 0.9999999998835847, \"rank\": 1.1642874822730957e-10, \"text\": \"Yeji\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\", \"Q215380\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Itzy\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Itzy\"}, {\"begin\": 2273, \"end\": 2279, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Punchy,_Somme\", \"score\": 0.6784377202962604, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Punchy\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Punchy,_Somme\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Punchy,_Somme\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply.\", \"from\": 2385, \"to\": 2516, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.\", \"from\": 2517, \"to\": 2689, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2579, \"end\": 2585, \"title\": \"http://dbp